It&#39;s a similar to the multiplexing problem that has been plaguing IEX...

It&#39;s a question with six inputs:

2 &quot;address lines&quot;
4 &quot;data lines&quot;

The problem is, treat the data lines as a 4-element array, treat the 
address lines as a 2 bit number, output the contents of the data array 
element indexed by the address lines.  For total clarity, in C, a solution 
would be:

int Multiplexer6(int addr0, int addr1, int data0, int data1, int data2, int 
data3) {
         int index = addr0 + (addr1 &lt;&lt; 1);
         int data[4];

         data[0] = data0;
         data[1] = data1;
         data[2] = data2;
         data[3] = data3;

         return data[index];
}

// note that all inputs and the output are constrained to 0 or 1

A similar standard test is the 11 multiplexer, where there are 8 data lines 
and 3 address lines.

I&#39;ve read her paper now.  Her neurones have a step activation function, and 
a threshold, they output 0 or 1 and everything is +ve.  This is in line 
with the standard GP multiplexing test case but it makes the logic simpler 
than if either the address or data were floats.

